# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: webtransport
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:webtransport/datagram] A **datagram** is a basic transfer unit associated with a packet-switched network.
[src:webtransport/datagram] Datagrams are typically structured in header and payload sections.
[src:webtransport/datagram] Datagrams provide a connectionless communication service across a packet-switched network.
[src:webtransport/datagram] The delivery, arrival time, and order of arrival of datagrams need not be guaranteed by the network.
[src:webtransport/datagram] In the early 1970s, the term *datagram* was created by combining the words *data* and *telegram* by the CCITT rapporteur on packet switching, Halvor Bothner-By.
[src:webtransport/datagram] While the word was new, the concept had already a long history.
[src:webtransport/datagram] In 1964, Paul Baran described, in a RAND Corporation report, a hypothetical military network having to resist a nuclear attack.
[src:webtransport/datagram] Small standardized *message blocks*, bearing source and destination addresses, were stored and forwarded in computer nodes of a highly redundant meshed computer network.
[src:webtransport/datagram] Baran wrote: "The network user who has called up a *virtual connection* to an end station and has transmitted messages ... might also view the system as a black box providing an apparent circuit connection".
[src:webtransport/datagram] The concept of what we now call a virtual circuit appears in the design, although no network was built.
[src:webtransport/datagram] In 1967, Donald Davies published a seminal article in which he introduced the *packet* and *packet switching*.
[src:webtransport/datagram] His proposed core network is similar to the one proposed by Paul Baran though developed independently.
[src:webtransport/datagram] He assumes that "all users of the network will provide themselves with some kind of error control".
[src:webtransport/datagram] His target is a "common-carrier communication network".
[src:webtransport/datagram] To support remote access to computer services by user terminals, which at that time were transmitted character by character, he included, at the network periphery, interface computers that convert character flows into packet flows and vice versa.
[src:webtransport/datagram] Wessler published an article about ARPANET, the first multi-node packet-switching network.
[src:webtransport/datagram] An accompanying paper described its switching nodes (the IMPs) and its packet formats.
[src:webtransport/datagram] The network core performed datagram switching as in Baran's and Davies' model, but the service offered to hosts by the network was connection oriented.
[src:webtransport/datagram] A reliable message transfer service was thus offered to user computers, thus greatly simplifying the network design.
[src:webtransport/datagram] This made the ARPANET what would come to be called a virtual circuit network.
[src:webtransport/datagram] Roberts presented the idea of packet switching to the communication professionals and faced anger and hostility.
[src:webtransport/datagram] Before ARPANET was operating, they argued that the router buffers would quickly run out.
[src:webtransport/datagram] After the ARPANET was operating, they argued packet switching would never be economic without the government subsidy.
[src:webtransport/datagram] Baran faced the same rejection and thus failed to convince the military to construct a packet-switching network.
[src:webtransport/datagram] In 1973, Louis Pouzin presented his design for CYCLADES, the first large-scale network implementing the pure Davies datagram model.
[src:webtransport/datagram] The CYCLADES team has thus been the first to tackle the highly complex problem of providing user applications a reliable virtual circuit service while using the end-to-end principle in a network service known to possibly produce non-negligible datagram losses and reordering.
[src:webtransport/datagram] In 1981, the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) issued the first specification the Internet Protocol (IP).
[src:webtransport/datagram] Network nodes may fragment a datagram into several smaller packets.
[src:webtransport/datagram] In 1999, the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) sanctioned the use of the already largely deployed network address translation (NAT) whereby each public address can be shared by several private devices.
[src:webtransport/datagram] With it, the forthcoming Internet Address exhaustion was delayed, leaving enough time to introduce IPv6, the new generation of Internet Protocol supporting longer addresses.
[src:webtransport/datagram] The initial principle of full end to end network transparency to datagrams was for this relaxed: NAT nodes had to manage per-connection states, making them in part connection oriented.
[src:webtransport/datagram] In 2015, the IETF upgraded its *informational* 1998 RFC 2309 that datagram switching nodes perform active queue management, to make it a stronger and more detailed *best current practice* recommendation through the publication of RFC 7567.
[src:webtransport/datagram] While the initial datagram queueing model was simple to implement and needed no more tuning than queue lengths, support of more sophisticated and parametrized mechanisms were found necessary "to improve and preserve Internet performance" (RED, ECN etc.).
[src:webtransport/datagram] Further research on the subject was also called for, with a list of identified items.
[src:webtransport/datagram] A datagram needs to be self-contained without reliance on earlier exchanges because there is no connection of fixed duration between the two communicating points as there is, for example, in most voice telephone conversations.
[src:webtransport/datagram] Datagram service is often compared to a mail delivery service; the user only provides the destination address but receives no guarantee of delivery, and no confirmation upon successful receipt.
[src:webtransport/datagram] Datagram service is therefore considered unreliable.
[src:webtransport/datagram] Datagram service routes datagrams without first creating a predetermined path.
[src:webtransport/datagram] Datagram service is therefore considered connectionless.
[src:webtransport/datagram] There is also no consideration given to the order in which it and other datagrams are sent or received.
[src:webtransport/datagram] In fact, many datagrams in the same group can travel along different paths before reaching the same destination in a different order.
[src:webtransport/datagram] Each datagram has two components, a header and a data payload.
[src:webtransport/datagram] The header contains all the information sufficient for routing from the originating equipment to the destination without relying on prior exchanges between the equipment and the network.
[src:webtransport/datagram] Headers may include source and destination addresses as well as type and length fields.
[src:webtransport/datagram] The payload is the data to be transported.
[src:webtransport/datagram] This process of nesting data payloads in a tagged header is called encapsulation.
[src:webtransport/datagram] The Internet Protocol (IP) defines standards for several types of datagrams.
[src:webtransport/datagram] The internet layer is a datagram service provided by an IP.
[src:webtransport/datagram] For example, UDP is run by a datagram service on the internet layer.
[src:webtransport/datagram] IP is an entirely connectionless, best effort, unreliable, message delivery service.
[src:webtransport/datagram] TCP is a higher-level protocol running on top of IP that provides a reliable connection-oriented service.
[src:webtransport/http] HTTP/3 uses similar semantics compared to earlier revisions of the protocol, including the same request methods, status codes, and message fields, but encodes them and maintains session state differently.
[src:webtransport/http] However, partially due to the protocol's adoption of QUIC, HTTP/3 has lower latency and loads more quickly in real-world usage when compared with previous versions: in some cases over four times faster than with HTTP/1.1 (which, for many websites, is the only HTTP version deployed).
[src:webtransport/http] As of September 2024, HTTP/3 is supported by more than 95% of major web browsers in use and 34% of the top 10 million websites.
[src:webtransport/http] It has been supported by Chromium (and derived projects including Google Chrome, Microsoft Edge, Samsung Internet, and Opera) since April 2020 and by Mozilla Firefox since May 2021.
[src:webtransport/http] HTTP/3 originates from an Internet Draft adopted by the QUIC working group.
[src:webtransport/http] The original proposal was named "HTTP/2 Semantics Using The QUIC Transport Protocol", and later renamed "Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) over QUIC".
[src:webtransport/http] On 28 October 2018 in a mailing list discussion, Mark Nottingham, Chair of the IETF HTTP and QUIC Working Groups, proposed renaming HTTP-over-QUIC to HTTP/3, to "clearly identify it as another binding of HTTP semantics to the wire protocol [...] so people understand its separation from QUIC".
[src:webtransport/http] Nottingham's proposal was accepted by fellow IETF members a few days later.
[src:webtransport/http] The HTTP working group was chartered to assist the QUIC working group during the design of HTTP/3, then assume responsibility for maintenance after publication.
[src:webtransport/http] Support for HTTP/3 was added to Chrome (Canary build) in September 2019 and then eventually reached stable builds, but was disabled by a feature flag.
[src:webtransport/http] It was enabled by default in April 2020.
[src:webtransport/http] Firefox added support for HTTP/3 in November 2019 through a feature flag and started enabling it by default in April 2021 in Firefox 88.
[src:webtransport/http] Experimental support for HTTP/3 was added to Safari Technology Preview on April 8, 2020 and was included with Safari 14 that ships with iOS 14 and macOS 11,.
[src:webtransport/http] Starting September 2024, HTTP/3 is supported for all users on Safari 16 or newer.
[src:webtransport/http] On 6 June 2022, IETF published HTTP/3 as a Proposed Standard in RFC 9114.
[src:webtransport/http] HTTP semantics are consistent across versions: the same request methods, status codes, and message fields are typically applicable to all versions.
[src:webtransport/http] The differences are in the mapping of these semantics to underlying transports.
[src:webtransport/http] Both HTTP/1.1 and HTTP/2 use TCP as their transport.
[src:webtransport/http] HTTP/3 uses QUIC, a transport layer network protocol which uses user space congestion control over the User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:webtransport/http] Because QUIC provides native multiplexing, lost packets only impact the streams where data has been lost.
[src:webtransport/http] The HTTPS DNS resource record as defined in RFC 9460 allows for connecting without first receiving the Alt-Svc header via previous HTTP versions, therefore removing the 1 RTT of handshaking of TCP.
[src:webtransport/http] There is client support for HTTPS resource records since Firefox 92, iOS 14, reported Safari 14 support, and Chromium supports it behind a flag.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] A **network socket** is a software structure within a network node of a computer network that serves as an endpoint for sending and receiving data across the network.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] The structure and properties of a socket are defined by an application programming interface (API) for the networking architecture.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Sockets are created only during the lifetime of a process of an application running in the node.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Because of the standardization of the TCP/IP protocols in the development of the Internet, the term *network socket* is most commonly used in the context of the Internet protocol suite, and is therefore often also referred to as **Internet socket**.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] In this context, a socket is externally identified to other hosts by its **socket address**, which is the triad of transport protocol, IP address, and port number.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] The term *socket* is also used for the software endpoint of node-internal inter-process communication (IPC), which often uses the same API as a network socket.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] The use of the term *socket* in software is analogous to the function of an electrical female connector, a device in hardware for communication between nodes interconnected with an electrical cable.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Similarly, the term *port* refers to external physical endpoints at a node or device.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] The application programming interface (API) for the network protocol stack creates a handle for each socket created by an application, commonly referred to as a *socket descriptor*.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] In Unix-like operating systems, this descriptor is a type of file descriptor.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] It is stored by the application process for use with every read and write operation on the communication channel.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] At the time of creation with the API, a network socket is bound to the combination of a type of network protocol to be used for transmissions, a network address of the host, and a port number.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Ports are numbered resources that represent another type of software structure of the node.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] They are used as service types, and, once created by a process, serve as an externally (from the network) addressable location component, so that other hosts may establish connections.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Network sockets may be dedicated for persistent connections for communication between two nodes, or they may participate in connectionless and multicast communications.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] In practice, due to the proliferation of the TCP/IP protocols in use on the Internet, the term *network socket* usually refers to use with the Internet Protocol (IP).
[src:webtransport/network-socket] It is therefore often also called **Internet socket**.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] An application can communicate with a remote process by exchanging data with TCP/IP by knowing the combination of protocol type, IP address, and port number.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] This combination is often known as a *socket address*.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] It is the network-facing access handle to the network socket.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] The remote process establishes a network socket in its own instance of the protocol stack and uses the networking API to connect to the application, presenting its own socket address for use by the application.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] A protocol stack, usually provided by the operating system (rather than as a separate library, for instance), is a set of services that allows processes to communicate over a network using the protocols that the stack implements.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] The operating system forwards the payload of incoming IP packets to the corresponding application by extracting the socket address information from the IP and transport protocol headers and stripping the headers from the application data.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] The application programming interface (API) that programs use to communicate with the protocol stack, using network sockets, is called a **socket API**.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Development of application programs that utilize this API is called *socket programming* or *network programming*.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Internet socket APIs are usually based on the Berkeley sockets standard.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] In the Berkeley sockets standard, sockets are a form of file descriptor, due to the Unix philosophy that "everything is a file", and the analogies between sockets and files.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Both have functions to read, write, open, and close.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] In practice, the differences strain the analogy, and different interfaces (send and receive) are used on a socket.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] In inter-process communication, each end generally has its own socket.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] In the standard Internet protocols TCP and UDP, a socket address is the combination of an IP address and a port number, much like one end of a telephone connection is the combination of a phone number and a particular extension.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Sockets need not have a source address, for example, for only sending data, but if a program *binds* a socket to a source address, the socket can be used to receive data sent to that address.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Based on this address, Internet sockets deliver incoming data packets to the appropriate application process.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] The distinctions between a socket (internal representation), socket descriptor (abstract identifier), and socket address (public address) are subtle, and these are not always distinguished in everyday usage.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Further, specific definitions of a *socket* differ between authors.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] In IETF Request for Comments, Internet Standards, in many textbooks, as well as in this article, the term *socket* refers to an entity that is uniquely identified by the socket number.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] In other textbooks, the term *socket* refers to a local socket address, i.e., a "combination of an IP address and a port number".
[src:webtransport/network-socket] In the original definition of *socket* given in RFC 147, as it was related to the ARPA network in 1971, *"the socket is specified as a 32-bit number with even sockets identifying receiving sockets and odd sockets identifying sending sockets."* Today, however, socket communications are bidirectional.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Within the operating system and the application that created a socket, a socket is referred to by a unique integer value called a *socket descriptor*.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] On Unix-like operating systems and Microsoft Windows, the command-line tools netstat or ss are used to list established sockets and related information.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] This example in Java, modeled according to the Berkeley socket interface, sends the string "Hello, world!" via TCP to port `80` of the host with address `203.0.113.0`.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Each packet sent or received on a datagram socket is individually addressed and routed.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Order and reliability are not guaranteed with datagram sockets, so multiple packets sent from one machine or process to another may arrive in any order or might not arrive at all.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] In order to receive broadcast packets, a datagram socket should not be bound to a specific address, though in some implementations, broadcast packets may also be received when a datagram socket is bound to a specific address.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] and unique flow of error-free data without record boundaries, with well-defined mechanisms for creating and destroying connections and reporting errors.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] On the Internet, stream sockets are typically implemented using TCP so that applications can run across any network using TCP/IP protocol.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Allow direct sending and receiving of IP packets without any protocol-specific transport layer formatting.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] according to the chosen transport layer protocol (e.g.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] When reading from a raw socket, the headers are usually included.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] When transmitting packets from a raw socket, the automatic addition of a header is optional.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] (APIs), for example, those based on Berkeley sockets, support raw sockets.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] interface, but three years later, Microsoft limited Winsock's raw socket support because of security concerns.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Other socket types are implemented over other transport protocols, such as Systems Network Architecture and Unix domain sockets for internal inter-process communication.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Computer processes that provide application services are referred to as servers, and create sockets on startup that are in the *listening state*.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] These sockets are waiting for initiatives from client programs.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] A TCP server may serve several clients concurrently by creating a unique dedicated socket for each client connection in a new child process or processing thread for each client.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] These are in the *established state* when a socket-to-socket virtual connection or virtual circuit (VC), also known as a TCP session, is established with the remote socket, providing a duplex byte stream.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] A server may create several concurrently established TCP sockets with the same local port number and local IP address, each mapped to its own server-child process, serving its own client process.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] They are treated as different sockets by the operating system since the remote socket address (the client IP address or port number) is different; i.e., since they have different socket pair tuples.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] UDP sockets do not have an *established state*, because the protocol is connectionless.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] A UDP server process handles incoming datagrams from all remote clients sequentially through the same socket.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] UDP sockets are not identified by the remote address, but only by the local address, although each message has an associated remote address that can be retrieved from each datagram with the networking application programming interface (API).
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Local and remote sockets communicating over TCP are called **socket pairs**.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Each socket pair is described by a unique 4-tuple consisting of source and destination IP addresses and port numbers, i.e. of local and remote socket addresses.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] As discussed above, in the TCP case, a socket pair is associated on each end of the connection with a unique 4-tuple.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] The term *socket* dates to the publication of RFC 147 in 1971, when it was used in the ARPANET.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Most modern implementations of sockets are based on Berkeley sockets (1983), and other stacks such as Winsock (1991).
[src:webtransport/network-socket] The Berkeley sockets API in the Berkeley Software Distribution (BSD) originated with the 4.2BSD Unix operating system as an API.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Only in 1989, however, could UC Berkeley release versions of its operating system and networking library free from the licensing constraints of AT&T's copyright-protected Unix.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] 1987, AT&T introduced the STREAMS-based Transport Layer Interface (TLI) in UNIX System V Release 3 (SVR3). and continued into Release 4 (SVR4).
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Other early implementations were written for TOPS-20, MVS, VM, IBM-DOS (PCIP).
[src:webtransport/network-socket] The socket is primarily a concept used in the transport layer of the Internet protocol suite or session layer of the OSI model.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Networking equipment such as routers, which operate at the internet layer, and switches, which operate at the link layer, do not require implementations of the transport layer.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] However, stateful network firewalls, network address translators, and proxy servers keep track of active socket pairs.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] In multilayer switches and quality of service (QoS) support in routers, packet flows may be identified by extracting information about the socket pairs.
[src:webtransport/network-socket] Raw sockets are typically available in network equipment and are used for routing protocols such as IGRP and OSPF, and for Internet Control Message Protocol (ICMP).
[src:webtransport/quic] QUIC improves performance of connection-oriented web applications that previously relied on Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:webtransport/quic] It does this by establishing a number of multiplexed connections between two endpoints using User Datagram Protocol (UDP), and it is designed to obsolete TCP at the transport layer for many applications.
[src:webtransport/quic] Although its name was initially proposed as an acronym for *Quick UDP Internet Connections*, in IETF's use of the word *QUIC* is not an acronym; it is simply the name of the protocol.
[src:webtransport/quic] QUIC works hand-in-hand with HTTP/3's multiplexed connections, allowing multiple streams of data to reach all the endpoints independently, and hence independent of packet losses involving other streams.
[src:webtransport/quic] In contrast, HTTP/2, which is carried over TCP, can suffer head-of-line-blocking delays if multiple streams are multiplexed on a TCP connection and any of the TCP packets on that connection are delayed or lost.
[src:webtransport/quic] QUIC's secondary goals include reduced connection and transport latency, and bandwidth estimation in each direction to avoid congestion.
[src:webtransport/quic] It also moves congestion control algorithms into the user space at both endpoints, rather than the kernel space, which is claimed to allow these algorithms to improve more rapidly.
[src:webtransport/quic] Additionally, the protocol can be extended with forward error correction (FEC) to further improve performance when errors are expected.
[src:webtransport/quic] It is designed with the intention of avoiding protocol ossification.
[src:webtransport/quic] In June 2015, an Internet Draft of a specification for QUIC was submitted to the IETF for standardization.
[src:webtransport/quic] A QUIC working group was established in 2016.
[src:webtransport/quic] In October 2018, the IETF's HTTP and QUIC Working Groups jointly decided to call the HTTP mapping over QUIC "HTTP/3" in advance of making it a worldwide standard.
[src:webtransport/quic] In May 2021, the IETF standardized QUIC in RFC 9000, supported by RFC 8999, 9001 and 9002.
[src:webtransport/quic] Transmission Control Protocol, or TCP, aims to provide an interface for sending streams of data between two endpoints.
[src:webtransport/quic] Data is sent to the TCP system, which ensures it reaches the other end in the exact same form; if any discrepancies occur, the connection will signal an error condition.
[src:webtransport/quic] To do this, TCP breaks up the data into network packets and adds small amounts of data to each packet.
[src:webtransport/quic] This additional data includes a sequence number that is used to detect packets that are lost or arrive out of order, and a checksum that allows the errors within packet data to be detected.
[src:webtransport/quic] When either problem occurs, TCP uses automatic repeat request (ARQ) to ask the sender to re-send the lost or damaged packet.
[src:webtransport/quic] In most implementations, TCP will see any error on a connection as a blocking operation, stopping further transfers until the error is resolved or the connection is considered failed.
[src:webtransport/quic] If a single connection is being used to send multiple streams of data, as is the case in the HTTP/2 protocol, all of these streams are blocked although only one of them might have a problem.
[src:webtransport/quic] For instance, if a single error occurs while downloading a GIF image used for a favicon, the entire rest of the page will wait while that problem is resolved.
[src:webtransport/quic] This phenomenon is known as head-of-line blocking.
[src:webtransport/quic] As the TCP system is designed to look like a "data pipe", or stream, it deliberately has little information regarding the data it transmits.
[src:webtransport/quic] If that data has additional requirements, like encryption using TLS, this must be set up by systems running on top of TCP, using TCP to communicate with similar software on the other end of the connection.
[src:webtransport/quic] Each of these sorts of setup tasks requires its own handshake process.
[src:webtransport/quic] This often requires several round-trips of requests and responses until the connection is established.
[src:webtransport/quic] Due to the inherent latency of long-distance communications, this can add significant delay to the overall transmission.
[src:webtransport/quic] TCP has suffered from protocol ossification, due to its wire image being in cleartext and hence visible to and malleable by middleboxes.
[src:webtransport/quic] One measurement found that a third of paths across the Internet encounter at least one intermediary that modifies TCP metadata, and 6.5% of paths encounter harmful ossifying effects from intermediaries.
[src:webtransport/quic] Extensions to TCP have been affected: the design of Multipath TCP (MPTCP) was constrained by middlebox behaviour, and the deployment of TCP Fast Open has been likewise hindered.
[src:webtransport/quic] In the context of supporting encrypted HTTP traffic, QUIC serves a role similar to that of TCP, but with reduced latency during connection setup and more efficient loss recovery when multiple HTTP streams are multiplexed over a single connection.
[src:webtransport/quic] It does this primarily through two changes that rely on the understanding of the behaviour of HTTP traffic.
[src:webtransport/quic] The first change is to greatly reduce overhead during connection setup.
[src:webtransport/quic] As most HTTP connections will demand TLS, QUIC makes the exchange of setup keys and listing of supported protocols part of the initial handshake process.
[src:webtransport/quic] When a client opens a connection, the response packet includes the data needed for future packets to use encryption.
[src:webtransport/quic] This eliminates the need to set up an unencrypted *pipe* and then negotiate the security protocol as separate steps.
[src:webtransport/quic] Other protocols can be serviced in the same way, combining multiple steps into a single request–response pair.
[src:webtransport/quic] This data can then be used both for following requests in the initial setup and future requests that would otherwise be negotiated as separate connections.
[src:webtransport/quic] The second change is to use UDP rather than TCP as its basis, which does not include loss recovery.
[src:webtransport/quic] Instead, each QUIC stream is separately flow-controlled, and lost data is retransmitted at the level of QUIC, not UDP.
[src:webtransport/quic] This means that if an error occurs in one stream, like the favicon example above, the protocol stack can continue servicing other streams independently.
[src:webtransport/quic] This can be very useful in improving performance on error-prone links, as in most cases considerable additional data may be received before TCP notices a packet is missing or broken, and all of this data is blocked or even flushed while the error is corrected.
[src:webtransport/quic] In QUIC, this data is free to be processed while the single multiplexed stream is repaired.
[src:webtransport/quic] QUIC includes a number of other changes that improve overall latency and throughput.
[src:webtransport/quic] For instance, the packets are encrypted individually, so that they do not result in the encrypted data waiting for partial packets.
[src:webtransport/quic] This is not generally possible under TCP, where the encryption records are in a bytestream and the protocol stack is unaware of higher-layer boundaries within this stream.
[src:webtransport/quic] These can be negotiated by the layers running on top, but QUIC aims to do all of this in a single handshake process.
[src:webtransport/quic] Another goal of the QUIC system was to improve performance during network-switching events, like what happens when a user of a mobile device moves from a local Wi-Fi hotspot to a mobile network.
[src:webtransport/quic] When this occurs on TCP, a lengthy process starts where every existing connection times out one-by-one and is then re-established on demand.
[src:webtransport/quic] To solve this problem, QUIC includes a connection identifier to uniquely identify the connection to the server regardless of source.
[src:webtransport/quic] This allows the connection to be re-established simply by sending a packet, which always contains this ID, as the original connection ID will still be valid even if the user's IP address changes.
[src:webtransport/quic] QUIC can be implemented in the application space, as opposed to being in the operating system kernel.
[src:webtransport/quic] This generally invokes additional overhead due to context switches as data is moved between applications.
[src:webtransport/quic] However, in the case of QUIC, the protocol stack is intended to be used by a single application, with each application using QUIC having its own connections hosted on UDP.
[src:webtransport/quic] Ultimately the difference could be very small because much of the overall HTTP/2 stack is already in the applications (or their libraries, more commonly).
[src:webtransport/quic] Placing the remaining parts in those libraries, essentially the error correction, has little effect on the HTTP/2 stack's size or overall complexity.
[src:webtransport/quic] This organization allows future changes to be made more easily as it does not require changes to the kernel for updates.
[src:webtransport/quic] One of QUIC's longer-term goals is to add new systems for forward error correction (FEC) and improved congestion control.
[src:webtransport/quic] One concern about the move from TCP to UDP is that TCP is widely adopted and many of the "middleboxes" in the Internet infrastructure are tuned for TCP and rate-limit or even block UDP.
[src:webtransport/quic] Google carried out a number of exploratory experiments to characterize this and found that only a small number of connections were blocked in this manner.
[src:webtransport/quic] This led to the use of a system for rapid fallback to TCP; Chromium's network stack starts both a QUIC and a conventional TCP connection at the same time, which allows it to fall back with negligible latency.
[src:webtransport/quic] QUIC has been specifically designed to be deployable and evolvable and to have anti-ossification properties; it is the first IETF transport protocol to deliberately minimise its wire image for these ends.
[src:webtransport/quic] Beyond encrypted headers, it is 'greased' and it has protocol invariants explicitly specified.
[src:webtransport/quic] The security layer of QUIC is based on TLS 1.2 or TLS 1.3.
[src:webtransport/quic] Earlier insecure protocols such as TLS 1.0 are not allowed in a QUIC stack.
[src:webtransport/quic] The protocol originally developed by Google, known as gQUIC, was first deployed around 2012 and later brought to the IETF.
[src:webtransport/quic] However, the version of QUIC standardized by the IETF is significantly different from the earlier Google implementation.
[src:webtransport/quic] Google's QUIC was initially designed as a general-purpose web protocol and was deployed mainly to support HTTP and HTTPS in Chromium, using its own encryption and transport mechanisms.
[src:webtransport/quic] In contrast, the IETF QUIC protocol has been redeveloped as a general-purpose transport protocol that uses standard TLS 1.3 for its cryptographic handshake and incorporates a modular packet and connection design intended for broader interoperability.
[src:webtransport/quic] Chromium developers have continued to follow the progress of IETF QUIC standardization and have worked to adopt and comply with the evolving Internet standards for QUIC within Chromium.
[src:webtransport/quic] The transition to IETF QUIC in Chrome began progressing publicly around 2020.
[src:webtransport/quic] QUIC was developed with HTTP in mind, and HTTP/3 was its first application.
[src:webtransport/quic] DNS-over-QUIC is an application of QUIC to name resolution, providing security for data transferred between resolvers similar to DNS-over-TLS.
[src:webtransport/quic] The IETF is developing applications of QUIC for secure network tunnelling and streaming media delivery.
[src:webtransport/quic] XMPP has experimentally been adapted to use QUIC.
[src:webtransport/quic] Another application is SMB over QUIC, which, according to Microsoft, can offer an "SMB VPN" without affecting the user experience.
[src:webtransport/quic] SMB clients use TCP by default and will attempt QUIC if the TCP attempt fails or if intentionally requiring QUIC.
[src:webtransport/quic] The QUIC code was experimentally developed in Google Chrome starting in 2012, and was announced as part of Chromium version 29 (released on August 20, 2013).
[src:webtransport/quic] It is currently enabled by default in Chromium and Chrome.
[src:webtransport/quic] Apple added experimental support in the WebKit engine through the Safari Technology Preview 104 in April 2020.
[src:webtransport/quic] Official support was added in Safari 14, included in macOS Big Sur and iOS 14, but the feature needed to be turned on manually.
[src:webtransport/quic] It was later enabled by default in Safari 16.
[src:webtransport/quic] The cronet library for QUIC and other protocols is available to Android applications as a module loadable via Google Play Services.
[src:webtransport/quic] cURL 7.66, released 11 September 2019, supports HTTP/3 (and thus QUIC).
[src:webtransport/quic] In October 2020, Facebook announced that it has successfully migrated its apps, including Instagram, and server infrastructure to QUIC, with already 75% of its Internet traffic using QUIC.
[src:webtransport/quic] All mobile apps from Google support QUIC, including YouTube and Gmail.
[src:webtransport/quic] As of 2017, there are several actively maintained implementations.
[src:webtransport/quic] Google servers support QUIC and Google has published a prototype server.
[src:webtransport/quic] Akamai Technologies has supported QUIC since July 2016.
[src:webtransport/quic] A Go implementation called quic-go is also available, and powers experimental QUIC support in the Caddy server.
[src:webtransport/quic] On July 11, 2017, LiteSpeed Technologies officially began supporting QUIC in their load balancer (WebADC) and LiteSpeed Web Server products.
[src:webtransport/quic] As of October 2019, 88.6% of QUIC websites used LiteSpeed and 10.8% used Nginx.
[src:webtransport/quic] Although at first only Google servers supported HTTP-over-QUIC connections, Facebook also launched the technology in 2018, and Cloudflare has been offering QUIC support on a beta basis since 2018.
[src:webtransport/quic] The HAProxy load balancer added experimental support for QUIC in March 2022 and declared it production-ready in March 2023.
[src:webtransport/quic] As of April 2023, 8.9% of all websites use QUIC, up from 5% in March 2021.
[src:webtransport/quic] Microsoft Windows Server 2022 supports both HTTP/3 and SMB over QUIC protocols via MsQuic.
[src:webtransport/quic] The Application Delivery Controller of Citrix (Citrix ADC, NetScaler) can function as a QUIC proxy since version 13.
[src:webtransport/quic] In addition, there are several stale community projects: libquic was created by extracting the Chromium implementation of QUIC and modifying it to minimize dependency requirements, and goquic provides Go bindings of libquic.
[src:webtransport/quic] Finally, quic-reverse-proxy is a Docker image that acts as a reverse proxy server, translating QUIC requests into plain HTTP that can be understood by the origin server.
[src:webtransport/quic] .NET 5 introduces experimental support for QUIC using the MsQuic library.
[src:webtransport/real-time-communication] Hard real-time communication systems are frequently electromechanically linked to a physical mechanism, often one that interfaces directly with people or property, which often contributes to or defines the potential danger of a fault.
[src:webtransport/real-time-communication] Due to their safety-critical nature, the communication protocols defined in a hard real-time system generally must be deterministic.
[src:webtransport/real-time-communication] Hard real-time communication systems are particularly common in the transportation, industrial, and medical sectors.
[src:webtransport/real-time-communication] Common applications include control systems, automotive controllers, medical devices, and critical safety systems such as airbag firing computers.
[src:webtransport/real-time-communication] Unlike hard real-time communication systems, soft real-time communication systems generally do not have the capacity to cause catastrophic harm upon a fault, which allows for non-deterministic, less rigorous network infrastructure.
[src:webtransport/real-time-communication] This allows soft real-time communication systems to operate over consumer networks such as residential internet connections and cellular networks.
[src:webtransport/real-time-communication] A large amount of soft real-time systems are telecommunications products such as VoIP systems and certain video calling platforms such as Discord and Google Meet.
[src:webtransport/real-time-communication] Data transmitted over a soft real-time communication system is not stored in a centralized server, and peers are connected directly to one another rather than through a server, although intermediary connecting nodes between peers are allowed when a direct link cannot be established.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS protocol aims primarily to provide security, including privacy (confidentiality), integrity, and authenticity through the use of cryptography, such as the use of certificates, between two or more communicating computer applications.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] It runs in the presentation layer and is itself composed of two layers: the TLS record and the TLS handshake protocols.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] The closely-related Datagram Transport Layer Security (DTLS) is a communications protocol that provides security to datagram-based applications.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] In technical writing, references to "(D)TLS" are often seen when it applies to both versions.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is a proposed Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) standard, first defined in 1999, and the current version is TLS 1.3, defined in August 2018.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS builds on the now-deprecated **SSL** (**Secure Sockets Layer**) specifications (1994, 1995, 1996) developed by Netscape Communications for adding the HTTPS protocol to their Netscape Navigator web browser.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Client–server applications use the TLS protocol to communicate across a network in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping and tampering.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Since applications can communicate either with or without TLS (or SSL), it is necessary for the client to request that the server set up a TLS connection.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] One of the main ways of achieving this is to use a different port number for TLS connections.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Port 80 is typically used for unencrypted HTTP traffic while port 443 is the common port used for encrypted HTTPS traffic.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Another mechanism is to make a protocol-specific STARTTLS request to the server to switch the connection to TLS – for example, when using some mail and news protocols.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Once the client and server have agreed to use TLS, they negotiate a stateful connection by using a handshaking procedure (see § TLS handshake).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] The protocols use a handshake with an asymmetric cipher to establish not only cipher settings but also a session-specific shared key with which further communication is encrypted using a symmetric cipher.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] This concludes the handshake and begins the secured connection, which is encrypted and decrypted with the session key until the connection closes.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] If any one of the above steps fails, then the TLS handshake fails and the connection is not created.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Note that TLS 1.3 only allows key exchange algorithms providing forward secrecy.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Consequently, establishing a PreMasterSecret using the server's public and private key is only available in TLS 1.2 and below.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS and SSL do not fit neatly into any single layer of the OSI model or the TCP/IP model.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS runs "on top of some reliable transport protocol (e.g., TCP)", which would imply that it is above the transport layer.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] It serves encryption to higher layers, which is normally the function of the presentation layer.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] However, applications generally use TLS as if it were a transport layer, even though applications using TLS must actively control initiating TLS handshakes and handling of exchanged authentication certificates.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS supports many different methods for exchanging keys, encrypting data, and authenticating message integrity.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, secure configuration of TLS involves many configurable parameters, and not all choices provide all of the privacy-related properties described in the list above (see the tables below § Key exchange, § Cipher security, and § Data integrity).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Attempts have been made to subvert aspects of the communications security that TLS seeks to provide, and the protocol has been revised several times to address these security threats.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Developers of web browsers have repeatedly revised their products to defend against potential security weaknesses after these were discovered (see TLS/SSL support history of web browsers).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Datagram Transport Layer Security, abbreviated DTLS, is a related communications protocol providing security to datagram-based applications by allowing them to communicate in a way designed to prevent eavesdropping, tampering, or message forgery.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] The DTLS protocol is based on the stream-oriented Transport Layer Security (TLS) protocol and is intended to provide similar security guarantees.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] As the DTLS protocol datagram preserves the semantics of the underlying transport, the application does not suffer from the delays associated with stream protocols.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] However, the application has to deal with packet reordering, loss of datagram and data larger than the size of a datagram network packet.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Because DTLS uses UDP or SCTP rather than TCP, it avoids the TCP meltdown problem, when being used to create a VPN tunnel.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] The original 2006 release of DTLS version 1.0 was not a standalone document.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given as a series of deltas to TLS 1.1.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Similarly the follow-up 2012 release of DTLS is a delta to TLS 1.2.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] It was given the version number of DTLS 1.2 to match its TLS version.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Lastly, the 2022 DTLS 1.3 is a delta to TLS 1.3.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Like the two previous versions, DTLS 1.3 is intended to provide "equivalent security guarantees [to TLS 1.3] with the exception of order protection/non-replayability".
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Many VPN clients including Cisco AnyConnect & InterCloud Fabric, OpenConnect, ZScaler tunnel, F5 Networks Edge VPN Client, and Citrix Systems NetScaler use DTLS to secure UDP traffic.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] In addition all modern web browsers support DTLS-SRTP for WebRTC.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] It was intended to complement the rapidly emerging new OSI internet standards moving forward both in the U.S. government's GOSIP Profiles and in the huge ITU-ISO JTC1 internet effort internationally.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] As part of the project, researchers designed a protocol called SP4 (*security protocol* in layer 4 of the OSI system).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] This was later renamed the Transport Layer Security Protocol (TLSP) and subsequently published in 1995 as international standard ITU-T X.274|ISO/IEC 10736:1995.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the name similarity, this is distinct from today's TLS.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] SNP was published and presented in the 1994 USENIX Summer Technical Conference.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] The SNP project was funded by a grant from NSA to Professor Simon Lam at UT-Austin in 1991.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Secure Network Programming won the 2004 ACM Software System Award.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Netscape developed the original SSL protocols, and Taher Elgamal, chief scientist at Netscape Communications from 1995 to 1998, has been described as the "father of SSL".
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL version 1.0 was never publicly released because of serious security flaws in the protocol.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Version 2.0, after being released in February 1995 was quickly found to contain a number of security and usability flaws.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] It used the same cryptographic keys for message authentication and encryption.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] It had a weak MAC construction that used the MD5 hash function with a secret prefix, making it vulnerable to length extension attacks.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] It also provided no protection for either the opening handshake or an explicit message close, both of which meant man-in-the-middle attacks could go undetected.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Moreover, SSL 2.0 assumed a single service and a fixed domain certificate, conflicting with the widely used feature of virtual hosting in Web servers, so most websites were effectively impaired from using SSL.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] These flaws necessitated the complete redesign of the protocol to SSL version 3.0.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Released in 1996, it was produced by Paul Kocher working with Netscape engineers Phil Karlton and Alan Freier, with a reference implementation by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Newer versions of SSL/TLS are based on SSL 3.0.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] The 1996 draft of SSL 3.0 was published by IETF as a historical document in RFC 6101.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 2.0 was deprecated in 2011 by RFC 6176.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2014, SSL 3.0 was found to be vulnerable to the POODLE attack that affects all block ciphers in SSL; RC4, the only non-block cipher supported by SSL 3.0, is also feasibly broken as used in SSL 3.0.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] SSL 3.0 was deprecated in June 2015 by RFC 7568.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 was first defined in RFC 2246 in January 1999 as an upgrade of SSL Version 3.0, and written by Christopher Allen and Tim Dierks of Certicom.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] As stated in the RFC, "the differences between this protocol and SSL 3.0 are not dramatic, but they are significant enough to preclude interoperability between TLS 1.0 and SSL 3.0".
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Tim Dierks later wrote that these changes, and the renaming from "SSL" to "TLS", were a face-saving gesture to Microsoft, "so it wouldn't look [like] the IETF was just rubberstamping Netscape's protocol".
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] The PCI Council suggested that organizations migrate from TLS 1.0 to TLS 1.1 or higher before June 30, 2018.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] In October 2018, Apple, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla jointly announced they would deprecate TLS 1.0 and 1.1 in March 2020.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 were formally deprecated in RFC 8996 in March 2021.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.1 was defined in RFC 4346 in April 2006.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS versions 1.0 and 1.1 was widely deprecated by web sites around 2020, disabling access to Firefox versions before 24 and Chromium-based browsers before 29, though third-party fixes can be applied to Netscape Navigator and older versions of Firefox to add TLS 1.2 support.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.2 was defined in RFC 5246 in August 2008.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.1 specification.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] All TLS versions were further refined in RFC 6176 in March 2011, removing their backward compatibility with SSL such that TLS sessions never negotiate the use of Secure Sockets Layer (SSL) version 2.0.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] As of April 2025 there is no formal date for TLS 1.2 to be deprecated.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was defined in RFC 8446 in August 2018.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] It is based on the earlier TLS 1.2 specification.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Network Security Services (NSS), the cryptography library developed by Mozilla and used by its web browser Firefox, enabled TLS 1.3 by default in February 2017.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 support was subsequently added — but due to compatibility issues for a small number of users, not automatically enabled — to Firefox 52.0, which was released in March 2017.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.3 was enabled by default in May 2018 with the release of Firefox 60.0.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Google Chrome set TLS 1.3 as the default version for a short time in 2017.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] It then removed it as the default, due to incompatible middleboxes such as Blue Coat web proxies.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] The intolerance of the new version of TLS was protocol ossification; middleboxes had ossified the protocol's version parameter.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] As a result, version 1.3 mimics the wire image of version 1.2.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] This change occurred very late in the design process, only having been discovered during browser deployment.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] The discovery of this intolerance also led to the prior version negotiation strategy, where the highest matching version was picked, being abandoned due to unworkable levels of ossification.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] 'Greasing' an extension point, where one protocol participant claims support for non-existent extensions to ensure that unrecognised-but-actually-existent extensions are tolerated and so to resist ossification, was originally designed for TLS, but it has since been adopted elsewhere.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] During the IETF 100 Hackathon, which took place in Singapore in 2017, the TLS Group worked on adapting open-source applications to use TLS 1.3.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS group was made up of individuals from Japan, United Kingdom, and Mauritius via the cyberstorm.mu team.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] This work was continued in the IETF 101 Hackathon in London, and the IETF 102 Hackathon in Montreal.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] wolfSSL enabled the use of TLS 1.3 as of version 3.11.1, released in May 2017.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] As the first commercial TLS 1.3 implementation, wolfSSL 3.11.1 supported Draft 18 and now supports Draft 28, the final version, as well as many older versions.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] A series of blogs were published on the performance difference between TLS 1.2 and 1.3.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] In September 2018, the popular OpenSSL project released version 1.1.1 of its library, in which support for TLS 1.3 was "the headline new feature".
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Support for TLS 1.3 was added to Secure Channel (schannel) for the GA releases of Windows 11 and Windows Server 2022.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] The Electronic Frontier Foundation praised TLS 1.3 and expressed concern about the variant protocol Enterprise Transport Security (ETS) that intentionally disables important security measures in TLS 1.3.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Originally called Enterprise TLS (eTLS), ETS is a published standard known as the 'ETSI TS103523-3', "Middlebox Security Protocol, Part3: Enterprise Transport Security".
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] It is intended for use entirely within proprietary networks such as banking systems.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] ETS does not support forward secrecy so as to allow third-party organizations connected to the proprietary networks to be able to use their private key to monitor network traffic for the detection of malware and to make it easier to conduct audits.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Despite the claimed benefits, the EFF warned that the loss of forward secrecy could make it easier for data to be exposed along with saying that there are better ways to analyze traffic.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] A digital certificate certifies the ownership of a public key by the named subject of the certificate, and indicates certain expected usages of that key.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] This allows others (relying parties) to rely upon signatures or on assertions made by the private key that corresponds to the certified public key.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Keystores and trust stores can be in various formats, such as .pem, .crt, .pfx, and .jks.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS typically relies on a set of trusted third-party certificate authorities to establish the authenticity of certificates.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Trust is usually anchored in a list of certificates distributed with user agent software, and can be modified by the relying party.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] According to Netcraft, who monitors active TLS certificates, the market-leading certificate authority (CA) has been Symantec since the beginning of their survey (or VeriSign before the authentication services business unit was purchased by Symantec).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] As of 2015, Symantec accounted for just under a third of all certificates and 44% of the valid certificates used by the 1 million busiest websites, as counted by Netcraft.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] In 2017, Symantec sold its TLS/SSL business to DigiCert.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] In an updated report, it was shown that IdenTrust, DigiCert, and Sectigo are the top 3 certificate authorities in terms of market share since May 2019.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] As a consequence of choosing X.509 certificates, certificate authorities and a public key infrastructure are necessary to verify the relation between a certificate and its owner, as well as to generate, sign, and administer the validity of certificates.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] On April 11, 2025, the CA/Browser Forum approved a ballot that will require all public TLS certificate lifespans to gradually reduce to 47 days by 2029.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Before a client and server can begin to exchange information protected by TLS, they must securely exchange or agree upon an encryption key and a cipher to use when encrypting data (see § Cipher).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] The TLS_DH_anon and TLS_ECDH_anon key agreement methods do not authenticate the server or the user and hence are rarely used because those are vulnerable to man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Only TLS_DHE and TLS_ECDHE provide forward secrecy.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Public key certificates used during exchange/agreement also vary in the size of the public/private encryption keys used during the exchange and hence the robustness of the security provided.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] In July 2013, Google announced that it would no longer use 1024-bit public keys and would switch instead to 2048-bit keys to increase the security of the TLS encryption it provides to its users because the encryption strength is directly related to the key size.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] If libraries implement fixes listed in RFC 5746, this violates the SSL 3.0 specification, which the IETF cannot change unlike TLS.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Most current libraries implement the fix and disregard the violation that this causes.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] The BEAST attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 and TLS 1.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] The POODLE attack breaks all block ciphers (CBC ciphers) used in SSL 3.0 unless mitigated by the client or the server.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] AEAD ciphers (such as GCM and CCM) can only be used in TLS 1.2 or later.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] CBC ciphers can be attacked with the Lucky Thirteen attack if the library is not written carefully to eliminate timing side channels.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] The Sweet32 attack breaks block ciphers with a block size of 64 bits.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Although the key length of 3DES is 168 bits, effective security strength of 3DES is only 112 bits, which is below the recommended minimum of 128 bits.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] IDEA and DES have been removed from TLS 1.2.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] 40-bit strength cipher suites were intentionally designed with reduced key lengths to comply with since-rescinded US regulations forbidding the export of cryptographic software containing certain strong encryption algorithms (see Export of cryptography from the United States).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] These weak suites are forbidden in TLS 1.1 and later.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Use of RC4 in all versions of TLS is prohibited because RC4 attacks weaken or break RC4 used in SSL/TLS.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] A message authentication code (MAC) is used for data integrity.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC is used for CBC mode of block ciphers.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Authenticated encryption (AEAD) such as GCM and CCM mode uses AEAD-integrated MAC and does not use HMAC.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] HMAC-based PRF, or HKDF is used for TLS handshake.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] In applications design, TLS is usually implemented on top of Transport Layer protocols, encrypting all of the protocol-related data of protocols such as HTTP, FTP, SMTP, NNTP and XMPP.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Historically, TLS has been used primarily with reliable transport protocols such as the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] However, it has also been implemented with datagram-oriented transport protocols, such as the User Datagram Protocol (UDP) and the Datagram Congestion Control Protocol (DCCP), usage of which has been standardized independently using the term *Datagram Transport Layer Security* (*DTLS*).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] A primary use of TLS is to secure World Wide Web traffic between a website and a web browser encoded with the HTTP protocol.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] This use of TLS to secure HTTP traffic constitutes the HTTPS protocol.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] As of March 2025, the latest versions of all major web browsers support TLS 1.2 and 1.3 and have them enabled by default, with the exception of IE 11.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS 1.0 and 1.1 are disabled by default on the latest versions of all major browsers.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Most SSL and TLS programming libraries are free and open-source software.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] A paper presented at the 2012 ACM conference on computer and communications security showed that many applications used some of these SSL libraries incorrectly, leading to vulnerabilities.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] The Simple Mail Transfer Protocol (SMTP) can also be protected by TLS.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] These applications use public key certificates to verify the identity of endpoints.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can also be used for tunneling an entire network stack to create a VPN, which is the case with OpenVPN and OpenConnect.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Many vendors have by now married TLS's encryption and authentication capabilities with authorization.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] There has also been substantial development since the late 1990s in creating client technology outside of Web-browsers, in order to enable support for client/server applications.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] Compared to traditional IPsec VPN technologies, TLS has some inherent advantages in firewall and NAT traversal that make it easier to administer for large remote-access populations.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS is also a standard method for protecting Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) application signaling.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p01] TLS can be used for providing authentication and encryption of the SIP signaling associated with VoIP and other SIP-based applications.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Significant attacks against TLS/SSL are listed below.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, IETF issued an informational RFC summarizing the various known attacks against TLS/SSL.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] A vulnerability of the renegotiation procedure was discovered in August 2009 that can lead to plaintext injection attacks against SSL 3.0 and all current versions of TLS.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] For example, it allows an attacker who can hijack an https connection to splice their own requests into the beginning of the conversation the client has with the web server.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacker cannot actually decrypt the client–server communication, so it is different from a typical man-in-the-middle attack.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] A short-term fix is for web servers to stop allowing renegotiation, which typically will not require other changes unless client certificate authentication is used.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] To fix the vulnerability, a renegotiation indication extension was proposed for TLS.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] It will require the client and server to include and verify information about previous handshakes in any renegotiation handshakes.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension has been implemented by several libraries.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] A protocol downgrade attack (also called a version rollback attack) tricks a web server into negotiating connections with previous versions of TLS (such as SSLv2) that have long since been abandoned as insecure.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Previous modifications to the original protocols, like **False Start** (adopted and enabled by Google Chrome) or **Snap Start**, reportedly introduced limited TLS protocol downgrade attacks or allowed modifications to the cipher suite list sent by the client to the server.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] In doing so, an attacker might succeed in influencing the cipher suite selection in an attempt to downgrade the cipher suite negotiated to use either a weaker symmetric encryption algorithm or a weaker key exchange.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] A paper presented at an ACM conference on computer and communications security in 2012 demonstrated that the False Start extension was at risk: in certain circumstances it could allow an attacker to recover the encryption keys offline and to access the encrypted data.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Encryption downgrade attacks can force servers and clients to negotiate a connection using cryptographically weak keys.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2014, a man-in-the-middle attack called FREAK was discovered affecting the OpenSSL stack, the default Android web browser, and some Safari browsers.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack involved tricking servers into negotiating a TLS connection using cryptographically weak 512 bit encryption keys.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Logjam is a security exploit discovered in May 2015 that exploits the option of using legacy "export-grade" 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups dating back to the 1990s.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] It forces susceptible servers to downgrade to cryptographically weak 512-bit Diffie–Hellman groups.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker can then deduce the keys the client and server determine using the Diffie–Hellman key exchange.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The DROWN attack is an exploit that attacks servers supporting contemporary SSL/TLS protocol suites by exploiting their support for the obsolete, insecure, SSLv2 protocol to leverage an attack on connections using up-to-date protocols that would otherwise be secure.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] DROWN exploits a vulnerability in the protocols used and the configuration of the server, rather than any specific implementation error.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Full details of DROWN were announced in March 2016, together with a patch for the exploit.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] At that time, more than 81,000 of the top 1 million most popular websites were among the TLS protected websites that were vulnerable to the DROWN attack.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Practical exploits had not been previously demonstrated for this vulnerability, which was originally discovered by Phillip Rogaway in 2002.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability of the attack had been fixed with TLS 1.1 in 2006, but TLS 1.1 had not seen wide adoption prior to this attack demonstration.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] RC4 as a stream cipher is immune to BEAST attack.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, RC4 was widely used as a way to mitigate BEAST attack on the server side.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] However, in 2013, researchers found more weaknesses in RC4.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Thereafter enabling RC4 on server side was no longer recommended.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Chrome and Firefox themselves are not vulnerable to BEAST attack, however, Mozilla updated their NSS libraries to mitigate BEAST-like attacks.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] NSS is used by Mozilla Firefox and Google Chrome to implement SSL.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Some web servers that have a broken implementation of the SSL specification may stop working as a result.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Microsoft released Security Bulletin MS12-006 on January 10, 2012, which fixed the BEAST vulnerability by changing the way that the Windows Secure Channel (Schannel) component transmits encrypted network packets from the server end.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Users of Internet Explorer (prior to version 11) that run on older versions of Windows (Windows 7, Windows 8 and Windows Server 2008 R2) can restrict use of TLS to 1.1 or higher.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Apple mitigated the BEAST vulnerability by implementing a 1/n-1 split and turning it on by default in OS X Mavericks, released on October 22, 2013.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The authors of the BEAST attack are also the creators of the later CRIME attack, which can allow an attacker to recover the content of web cookies when data compression is used along with TLS.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] When used to recover the content of secret authentication cookies, it allows an attacker to perform session hijacking on an authenticated web session.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The CRIME exploit against HTTP compression has not been mitigated at all, even though the authors of CRIME have warned that this vulnerability might be even more widespread than SPDY and TLS compression combined.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2013 a new instance of the CRIME attack against HTTP compression, dubbed BREACH, was announced.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] All versions of TLS and SSL are at risk from BREACH regardless of the encryption algorithm or cipher used.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a known limitation of TLS as it is susceptible to chosen-plaintext attack against the application-layer data it was meant to protect.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Earlier TLS versions were vulnerable against the padding oracle attack discovered in 2002.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] A novel variant, called the Lucky Thirteen attack, was published in 2013.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Some experts also recommended avoiding triple DES CBC.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] A fix was released in 2014 as the Encrypt-then-MAC extension to the TLS specification.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The Lucky Thirteen attack can be mitigated in TLS 1.2 by using only AES_GCM ciphers; AES_CBC remains vulnerable.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] SSL may safeguard email, VoIP, and other types of communications over insecure networks in addition to its primary use case of secure data transmission between a client and the server.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] On October 14, 2014, Google researchers published a vulnerability in the design of SSL 3.0, which makes CBC mode of operation with SSL 3.0 vulnerable to a padding attack (CVE-2014-3566).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] They named this attack **POODLE** (**Padding Oracle On Downgraded Legacy Encryption**).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] On average, attackers only need to make 256 SSL 3.0 requests to reveal one byte of encrypted messages.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Therefore, the man-in-the-middle can first conduct a version rollback attack and then exploit this vulnerability.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] On December 8, 2014, a variant of POODLE was announced that impacts TLS implementations that do not properly enforce padding byte requirements.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Despite the existence of attacks on RC4 that broke its security, cipher suites in SSL and TLS that were based on RC4 were still considered secure prior to 2013 based on the way in which they were used in SSL and TLS.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] In 2011, the RC4 suite was actually recommended as a workaround for the BEAST attack.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] New forms of attack disclosed in March 2013 conclusively demonstrated the feasibility of breaking RC4 in TLS, suggesting it was not a good workaround for BEAST.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack scenario was proposed by AlFardan, Bernstein, Paterson, Poettering and Schuldt that used newly discovered statistical biases in the RC4 key table to recover parts of the plaintext with a large number of TLS encryptions.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] An attack on RC4 in TLS and SSL that requires 13 × 220 encryptions to break RC4 was unveiled on 8 July 2013 and later described as "feasible" in the accompanying presentation at a USENIX Security Symposium in August 2013.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] In July 2015, subsequent improvements in the attack make it increasingly practical to defeat the security of RC4-encrypted TLS.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] As many modern browsers have been designed to defeat BEAST attacks (except Safari for Mac OS X 10.7 or earlier, for iOS 6 or earlier, and for Windows; see § Web browsers), RC4 is no longer a good choice for TLS 1.0.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The CBC ciphers which were affected by the BEAST attack in the past have become a more popular choice for protection.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Mozilla and Microsoft recommend disabling RC4 where possible.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, the use of RC4 cipher suites was officially prohibited in all versions of TLS.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] On September 1, 2015, Microsoft, Google, and Mozilla announced that RC4 cipher suites would be disabled by default in their browsers (Microsoft Edge [Legacy], Internet Explorer 11 on Windows 7/8.1/10, Firefox, and Chrome) in early 2016.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] A TLS (logout) truncation attack blocks a victim's account logout requests so that the user unknowingly remains logged into a web service.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] When the request to sign out is sent, the attacker injects an unencrypted TCP FIN message (no more data from sender) to close the connection.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The server therefore does not receive the logout request and is unaware of the abnormal termination.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The attack does not rely on installing malware on the victim's computer; attackers need only place themselves between the victim and the web server (e.g., by setting up a rogue wireless hotspot).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This vulnerability also requires access to the victim's computer.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Another possibility is when using FTP the data connection can have a false FIN in the data stream, and if the protocol rules for exchanging close_notify alerts is not adhered to a file can be truncated.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2013 two researchers from Royal Holloway, University of London discovered a timing attack which allowed them to recover (parts of the) plaintext from a DTLS connection using the OpenSSL or GnuTLS implementation of DTLS when Cipher Block Chaining mode encryption was used.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, discovered in mid-2016, exploits weaknesses in the Web Proxy Autodiscovery Protocol (WPAD) to expose the URL that a web user is attempting to reach via a TLS-enabled web link.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Disclosure of a URL can violate a user's privacy, not only because of the website accessed, but also because URLs are sometimes used to authenticate users.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Document sharing services, such as those offered by Google and Dropbox, also work by sending a user a security token that is included in the URL.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] An attacker who obtains such URLs may be able to gain full access to a victim's account or data.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The exploit works against almost all browsers and operating systems.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The Sweet32 attack breaks all 64-bit block ciphers used in CBC mode as used in TLS by exploiting a birthday attack and either a man-in-the-middle attack or injection of a malicious JavaScript into a web page.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The purpose of the man-in-the-middle attack or the JavaScript injection is to allow the attacker to capture enough traffic to mount a birthday attack.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug is a serious vulnerability specific to the implementation of SSL/TLS in the popular OpenSSL cryptographic software library, affecting versions 1.0.1 to 1.0.1f.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This weakness, reported in April 2014, allows attackers to extract private keys from servers that should normally be protected.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The Heartbleed bug allows anyone on the Internet to read the memory of the systems protected by the vulnerable versions of the OpenSSL software.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This compromises the secret private keys associated with the public certificates used to identify the service providers and to encrypt the traffic, the names and passwords of the users and the actual content.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This allows attackers to eavesdrop on communications, extract data directly from the services and users and to impersonate services and users.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The vulnerability is caused by a buffer over-read bug in the OpenSSL software, rather than a defect in the SSL or TLS protocol specification.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] In September 2014, a variant of Daniel Bleichenbacher's PKCS#1 v1.5 RSA Signature Forgery vulnerability was announced by Intel Security Advanced Threat Research.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This attack, dubbed BERserk, is a result of incomplete ASN.1 length decoding of public key signatures in some SSL implementations, and allows a man-in-the-middle attack by forging a public key signature.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2015, after media reported the hidden pre-installation of superfish adware on some Lenovo notebooks, a researcher found a trusted root certificate on affected Lenovo machines to be insecure, as the keys could easily be accessed using the company name, Komodia, as a passphrase.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The Komodia library was designed to intercept client-side TLS/SSL traffic for parental control and surveillance, but it was also used in numerous adware programs, including Superfish, that were often surreptitiously installed unbeknownst to the computer user.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] In turn, these potentially unwanted programs installed the corrupt root certificate, allowing attackers to completely control web traffic and confirm false websites as authentic.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] In May 2016, it was reported that dozens of Danish HTTPS-protected websites belonging to Visa Inc. were vulnerable to attacks allowing hackers to inject malicious code and forged content into the browsers of visitors.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The attacks worked because the TLS implementation used on the affected servers incorrectly reused random numbers (nonces) that are intended to be used only once, ensuring that each TLS handshake is unique.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] In February 2017, an implementation error caused by a single mistyped character in code used to parse HTML created a buffer overflow error on Cloudflare servers.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Similar in its effects to the Heartbleed bug discovered in 2014, this overflow error, widely known as Cloudbleed, allowed unauthorized third parties to read data in the memory of programs running on the servers—data that should otherwise have been protected by TLS.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] As of June 2025, the Trustworthy Internet Movement estimated the ratio of websites that are vulnerable to TLS attacks.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Forward secrecy is a property of cryptographic systems which ensures that a session key derived from a set of public and private keys will not be compromised if one of the private keys is compromised in the future.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] An implementation of TLS can provide forward secrecy by requiring the use of ephemeral Diffie–Hellman key exchange to establish session keys, and some notable TLS implementations do so exclusively: e.g., Gmail and other Google HTTPS services that use OpenSSL.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] However, many clients and servers supporting TLS (including browsers and web servers) are not configured to implement such restrictions.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] In practice, unless a web service uses Diffie–Hellman key exchange to implement forward secrecy, all of the encrypted web traffic to and from that service can be decrypted by a third party if it obtains the server's master (private) key; e.g., by means of a court order.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Even where Diffie–Hellman key exchange is implemented, server-side session management mechanisms can impact forward secrecy.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of TLS session tickets (a TLS extension) causes the session to be protected by AES128-CBC-SHA256 regardless of any other negotiated TLS parameters, including forward secrecy ciphersuites, and the long-lived TLS session ticket keys defeat the attempt to implement forward secrecy.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Stanford University research in 2014 also found that of 473,802 TLS servers surveyed, 82.9% of the servers deploying ephemeral Diffie–Hellman (DHE) key exchange to support forward secrecy were using weak Diffie–Hellman parameters.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] These weak parameter choices could potentially compromise the effectiveness of the forward secrecy that the servers sought to provide.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Since late 2011, Google has provided forward secrecy with TLS by default to users of its Gmail service, along with Google Docs and encrypted search, among other services.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Since November 2013, Twitter has provided forward secrecy with TLS to users of its service.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] As of August 2019, about 80% of TLS-enabled websites are configured to use cipher suites that provide forward secrecy to most web browsers.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS interception (or HTTPS interception if applied particularly to that protocol) is the practice of intercepting an encrypted data stream in order to decrypt it, read and possibly manipulate it, and then re-encrypt it and send the data on its way again.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This is done by way of a "transparent proxy": the interception software terminates the incoming TLS connection, inspects the HTTP plaintext, and then creates a new TLS connection to the destination.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS/HTTPS interception is used as an information security measure by network operators in order to be able to scan for and protect against the intrusion of malicious content into the network, such as computer viruses and other malware.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Such content could otherwise not be detected as long as it is protected by encryption, which is increasingly the case as a result of the routine use of HTTPS and other secure protocols.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] A significant drawback of TLS/HTTPS interception is that it introduces new security risks of its own.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] One notable limitation is that it provides a point where network traffic is available unencrypted thus giving attackers an incentive to attack this point in particular in order to gain access to otherwise secure content.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The interception also allows the network operator, or persons who gain access to its interception system, to perform man-in-the-middle attacks against network users.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] A 2017 study found that "HTTPS interception has become startlingly widespread, and that interception products as a class have a dramatically negative impact on connection security".
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS protocol exchanges *records*, which encapsulate the data to be exchanged in a specific format (see below).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record can be compressed, padded, appended with a message authentication code (MAC), or encrypted, all depending on the state of the connection.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Each record has a *content type* field that designates the type of data encapsulated, a length field and a TLS version field.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The data encapsulated may be control or procedural messages of the TLS itself, or simply the application data needed to be transferred by TLS.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The specifications (cipher suite, keys etc.) required to exchange application data by TLS, are agreed upon in the "TLS handshake" between the client requesting the data and the server responding to requests.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The protocol therefore defines both the structure of payloads transferred in TLS and the procedure to establish and monitor the transfer.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] When the connection starts, the record encapsulates a "control" protocol – the handshake messaging protocol (*content type* 22).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This protocol is used to exchange all the information required by both sides for the exchange of the actual application data by TLS.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines the format of messages and the order of their exchange.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] These may vary according to the demands of the client and server – i.e., there are several possible procedures to set up the connection.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This initial exchange results in a successful TLS connection (both parties ready to transfer application data with TLS) or an alert message (as specified below).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Application phase: at this point, the "handshake" is complete and the application protocol is enabled, with content type of 23.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be authenticated and optionally encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the content type will return 25 and the client will not authenticate.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The following *full* example shows a client being authenticated (in addition to the server as in the example above; see mutual authentication) via TLS using certificates exchanged between both peers.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The client now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the server, "Everything I tell you from now on will be authenticated (and encrypted if encryption was negotiated).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] "The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Application messages exchanged between client and server will also be encrypted exactly like in their *Finished* message.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Public key operations (e.g., RSA) are relatively expensive in terms of computational power.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] TLS provides a secure shortcut in the handshake mechanism to avoid these operations: resumed sessions.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Resumed sessions are implemented using session IDs or session tickets.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Apart from the performance benefit, resumed sessions can also be used for single sign-on, as it guarantees that both the original session and any resumed session originate from the same client.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This is of particular importance for the FTP over TLS/SSL protocol, which would otherwise suffer from a man-in-the-middle attack in which an attacker could intercept the contents of the secondary data connections.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The TLS 1.3 handshake was condensed to only one round trip compared to the two round trips required in previous versions of TLS/SSL.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] To start the handshake, the client guesses which key exchange algorithm will be selected by the server and sends a **ClientHello** message to the server containing a list of supported ciphers (in order of the client's preference) and public keys for some or all of its key exchange guesses.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] If the client successfully guesses the key exchange algorithm, 1 round trip is eliminated from the handshake.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] After receiving the **ClientHello**, the server selects a cipher and sends back a **ServerHello** with its own public key, followed by server **Certificate** and **Finished** messages.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] After the client receives the server's finished message, it now is coordinated with the server on which cipher suite to use.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] In an ordinary *full* handshake, the server sends a *session id* as part of the **ServerHello** message.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The client associates this *session id* with the server's IP address and TCP port, so that when the client connects again to that server, it can use the *session id* to shortcut the handshake.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] In the server, the *session id* maps to the cryptographic parameters previously negotiated, specifically the "master secret".
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Both sides must have the same "master secret" or the resumed handshake will fail (this prevents an eavesdropper from using a *session id*).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The random data in the **ClientHello** and **ServerHello** messages virtually guarantee that the generated connection keys will be different from in the previous connection.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] In the RFCs, this type of handshake is called an *abbreviated* handshake.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] It is also described in the literature as a *restart* handshake.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The server now sends a **ChangeCipherSpec** record, essentially telling the client, "Everything I tell you from now on will be encrypted." The ChangeCipherSpec is itself a record-level protocol and has type 20 and not 22.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Instead of session IDs, TLS can also be extended via use of session tickets.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] It defines a way to resume a TLS session without requiring that session-specific state is stored at the TLS server.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] When using session tickets, the TLS server stores its session-specific state in a session ticket and sends the session ticket to the TLS client for storing.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The client resumes a TLS session by sending the session ticket to the server, and the server resumes the TLS session according to the session-specific state in the ticket.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The session ticket is encrypted and authenticated by the server, and the server verifies its validity before using its contents.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] One particular weakness of this method with OpenSSL is that it always limits encryption and authentication security of the transmitted TLS session ticket to `AES128-CBC-SHA256`, no matter what other TLS parameters were negotiated for the actual TLS session.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the state information (the TLS session ticket) is not as well protected as the TLS session itself.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This is the general format of all TLS records.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the Record Layer Protocol Type contained in this record.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the major and minor version of TLS prior to TLS 1.3 for the contained message.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] and application must send supported versions in an extra message extension block.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] One or more messages identified by the Protocol field.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that this field may be encrypted depending on the state of the connection.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] field, with additional key material included.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Most messages exchanged during the setup of the TLS session are based on this record, unless an error or warning occurs and needs to be signaled by an Alert protocol record (see below), or the encryption mode of the session is modified by another record (see **ChangeCipherSpec** protocol below).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the handshake message type.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a 3-byte field indicating the length of the handshake data, not including the header.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Note that multiple handshake messages may be combined within one record.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This record should normally not be sent during normal handshaking or application exchanges.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] However, this message can be sent at any time during the handshake and up to the closure of the session.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] If this is used to signal a fatal error, the session will be closed immediately after sending this record, so this record is used to give a reason for this closure.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] If the alert level is flagged as a warning, the remote can decide to close the session if it decides that the session is not reliable enough for its needs (before doing so, the remote may also send its own signal).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 2.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the level of alert.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] If the level is fatal, the sender should close the session immediately.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Otherwise, the recipient may decide to terminate the session itself, by sending its own fatal alert and closing the session itself immediately after sending it.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The use of Alert records is optional, however if it is missing before the session closure, the session may be resumed automatically (with its handshakes).
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Alert type (with a simple warning level) to prevent such automatic resume of a new session.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies which type of alert is being sent.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The length of the rest of fields, which is 1.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This field identifies the CCS Protocol type.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] The last byte contains the padding length.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] From the application protocol point of view, TLS belongs to a lower layer, although the TCP/IP model is too coarse to show it.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This means that the TLS handshake is usually (except in the STARTTLS case) performed before the application protocol can start.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] In the name-based virtual server feature being provided by the application layer, all co-hosted virtual servers share the same certificate because the server has to select and send a certificate immediately after the ClientHello message.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This is a big problem in hosting environments because it means either sharing the same certificate among all customers or using a different IP address for each of them.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] To provide the server name, Transport Layer Security (TLS) Extensions allow clients to include a Server Name Indication extension (SNI) in the extended ClientHello message.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This extension hints to the server immediately which name the client wishes to connect to, so the server can select the appropriate certificate to send to the clients.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] There is also a method to implement name-based virtual hosting by upgrading HTTP to TLS via an HTTP/1.1 Upgrade header.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] Normally this is to securely implement HTTP over TLS within the main "http" URI scheme instead of the commonly used "https" scheme.
[src:webtransport/transport-layer-security-p02] This would avoid forking the URI space and reduces the number of used ports, however, few implementations currently support this.
